Three main scenarios are possible in today’s parliamentary session in Iraq:
* Session held and a president is chosen
* Session held but no candidate gets the two-thirds majority needed to get the post
* Session fails to meet the threshold of 220 MPs and thus no quorum

Regardless of which candidate they support, MPs should turn up and cast their votes. Rumours of MPs pretending to be sick or finding excuses not to attend in order to make sure quorum is not met is shameful. The failure of a session today means greater dysfunction for Iraq

In a few hours, Iraq’s parliament is meant to hold a session with only 1 item on the agenda - to select a president. Rather than all MPs turning up and doing their job, which they get paid handsomely for, rumours abound that some will stay away to stop session from happening
